Project Overview (This can be a group project of team of 2)
Students will design, implement, test, and present a multi-device, accessible, performance-optimized website (or web app) for a real or realistic client (examples: university departmental site, research group portal, local business, digital portfolio, library/catalog). The project must demonstrate mastery of:

Visual design principles, information architecture, and navigation.

CSS page layout techniques: box model, Flexbox/Grid, floats/clears, positioning, stacking, and responsive behaviors.

Accessibility (WCAG/POUR), semantic HTML, and mobile-first responsive design.

Progressive enhancement, performance optimization, and maintainable code structure.

Students will produce a production-ready codebase, documentation, automated tests (unit/integration or end-to-end), a deployment, and a recorded final presentation.

Learning Objectives (What students will prove)
By the end of the project students will be able to:

Produce a semantically structured, accessible multi-page website or SPA that adheres to WCAG principles.

Apply advanced CSS layout techniques (box model, Flexbox/Grid, floats, relative/absolute/sticky positioning) to create responsive designs for multiple breakpoints.

Design clear information architecture and navigation (hierarchical vs. linear) that supports usability and findability.

Optimize assets and layout for performance (images, sprites, critical CSS, lazy loading).

Implement client-side interactivity (search/filter, dynamic content updates) without sacrificing accessibility or progressive enhancement.

Document design decisions with a professional artifact (README, architecture diagram, accessibility report, test plan) and present results.

Project Scope & Requirements
A. Core Deliverable (Required)
A complete website or web app that includes:

Home + 4 additional pages or SPA sections (e.g., About, Catalog/Products, Resources/Blog, Contact).

Responsive layout implemented with CSS Grid and/or Flexbox; layout must demonstrate mastery of box model, margins, padding, and box-sizing.

Accessible navigation: semantic <nav>, skip links, keyboard focus styles, readable link text, and breadcrumb or other aids for deep hierarchies.

Design system basics: a consistent color scheme (with contrast checks), typography scale, spacing system, and UI component library (buttons, forms, cards).

Interactive components: searchable/filterable item list (debounced search), modal or detail view, client-side form with validation. Interactivity must function without JavaScript where reasonable (graceful degradation/progressive enhancement).

Advanced CSS features: pseudo-classes for links, CSS sprites or optimized imagery, print stylesheet, and sticky/fixed navigation usage where appropriate.

Performance considerations: image optimization (responsive images / srcset), minimized CSS/JS, and lazy loading of non-critical assets.

Accessibility audit: run and include results from at least two tools (e.g., WAVE, aXe, Lighthouse), plus a manual checklist covering WCAG POUR principles.

B. Technical Stack (choose one path)
Option 1 — Static / Progressive Enhancement (Recommended for design focus)
Vanilla HTML5, semantic elements

CSS (Sass optional) with Grid/Flexbox

Minimal JS (ES6+) for interactivity (search, modal)

Build step optional (parcel/webpack)
Why choose: Emphasis on layout, semantics, accessibility.

Option 2 — Single Page Application (for engineering focus)
React (functional components) OR Vue

CSS Modules / Tailwind / Sass (student choice)

State management via Context or local component state

Client-side routing for pages
Extra credit: server-side rendering (Next.js) or hydration

C. Optional Back End (extra credit / advanced)
Provide a simple API for dynamic content (Node.js + Express + SQLite or MongoDB).

Implement server-side search and pagination; protect against injection; document endpoints.
Note: Back end is optional unless course requires full-stack; front end must work without it (mock JSON acceptable).

